g all incoming requests.\n\nFor the normal business processing completion flow, I'm checking the full handler chain from WebFrontController through the inbound handlers—SessionConcurrentAccessHandler, ThreadContextHandler, HttpAccessLogHandler, NablarchTagHandler, DbConnectionManagementHandler, TransactionManagementHandler, and the mapping/binding handlers—then tracing back through the outbound sequence including TransactionManagementHandler, DbConnectionManagementHandler, HttpAccessLogHandler, and HttpResponseHandler.\n\nThe knowledge file confirms this matches the documented flow with the default status code 200 returned through SessionConcurrentAccessHandler back to WebFrontController. Now I'm looking at the user error flow. I'm seeing how NullPointerException and other runtime errors flow through the transaction and database handlers before reaching the error handler, which logs the failure and returns a 500 response. Then there are two other request patterns: direct JSP access that bypasses most handlers, and internal forwards that follow a similar initial path through the session and context handlers.\n\nFor file uploads exceeding the size limit, the MultipartHandler catches this during the inbound phase and throws a 400 error immediately, which then gets processed through the error handler and response chain. I'm verifying each of these flows against the knowledge file to make sure the documented behavior matches what's actually happening in the source code. I'm verifying the forward flow path against the source—it correctly omits HttpResponseHandler, SessionConcurrentAccessHandler, and WebFrontController from the outbound sequence, which distinguishes it from the normal end flow. Now I'm checking what else the source table specifies about the standard handler...\n\nThe authorization and service status error flows are referenced in the source but lack detailed handler-level breakdowns in the JavaScript, so the knowledge file appropriately includes them in the